I think the primary reason that self-defense killing is tolerated (and often
considered necessary) by Muggles is that there is no other alternative: you
must either kill or be killed.  With the advent of magic, however, I'm not
sure this still holds.  Is there any situation in which you really must kill
someone, if you have the ability to Stun them or place them under a full
body-bind instead?  I can't think of any.

Witness the seven HP books: only once does a good character feel the need to
use AK, and then only under extreme, extenuating circumstances.  Also
witness Harry's mercy at the beginning of DH: not only does he not kill
Stan, but he merely disarms him!  The presence of magic opens up a new
spectrum of possibilities for countering personal threats without killing
and, in some cases, without even causing physical harm.

(I can perhaps imagine that there some desperate situations in which the
only option is to use the Imperius Curse, so this one is—maybe—sometimes
forgivable.  As for the Cruciatus and AK, however, there is no excuse.  The
Cruciatus in particular has even fewer legitimate uses than the Killing
Curse.)

